## CODE QUALITY STANDARDS

### Always
- Match the existing code style exactly (indentation, naming, patterns)
- Handle errors explicitly — no silent failures, no bare `except`, no unhandled promise rejections
- Validate inputs at boundaries
- Write code that is readable without needing comments to explain basic logic
- Use comments only for non-obvious decisions or "why", never for "what"

### Never
- Leave TODO/placeholder code in delivered output unless explicitly asked
- Hardcode secrets, credentials, or environment-specific values
- Break existing interfaces or APIs without flagging it as a breaking change
- Add dependencies without stating why the existing stack couldn't handle it

